	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=/db/item.html?item=5595&mid=103428434295334>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=/db/item.html?item=5595&mid=103428434295334>You forgot one thing, Kaeln</a> <a id=fs8 href=/db/item.html?item=5595&mid=103428434295334#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Thu, Oct 10th 5:30 PM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=608><span id=Scholar>Nexroth</span></a><br><b><span id=Scholar>Scholar</span></b><br><span id=notbold>28 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [2.90]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>The scale should be set so that all store bought instruments have a bonus of zero.&nbsp;&nbsp;Not using the proper instrument is usually considered a penalty.  With that in mind, you can reconfigure your data so that Ervaj's Flute of Flight provides +5 to the standard 25, or a 20% bonus ((test stat - store instrument stat)/store instrument stat).  Lyssa's Darkwood Piccolo gives +8 or a 32% bonus.  ((33-25)/25) = 8/25 or .32<br><br>This is the best method for creating some standardization for instrument bonuses using a percentage.<br><br></p>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
